16. Tela: fulmina. -cyelopum the Cyclopes were repre- sented in the Odyssey as a race of giants given to caunibalism. They dwelt in caves on the mountain sides of an island which was afterwards identified with Sicily. They knew nothing of the arts of civilization, and feared neither gods nor men. Hesiod names three, Brontes Steropes and Arges. The later poets represent them as using the caverns'of Mount Etna for their smithy.
